{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"249d266e-5d62-45f5-b37e-72d8ca2214f9","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"tooluse_PrVZbWWE7dJVb6RGSpLbsA","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Creating .NET 11 console app"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"tooluse_UbMGhhnykJnleuMD8Ferdv","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"dotnet --version 2>/dev/null; dotnet --list-sdks 2>/dev/null | tail -5","description":"Check available .NET SDKs","initial_wait":10},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Check available .NET SDKs"}],"interactionId":"192dd26e-1165-4327-8164-2087c3b07f2c","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants a .NET 11 console app that serializes a `Person` record to JSON with PascalCase property names using built-in framework features.\n\nIn .NET 9+, `System.Text.Json` added `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` as a built-in naming policy. Since the record has lowercase parameter names (`name`, `age`), the generated properties will be lowercase by default in JSON serialization. Using `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` will convert them to `Name` and `Age`.\n\nWait, let me think about this more carefully. In C#, when you define `public record Person(string name, int age)`, the compiler generates properties `name` and `age` (with lowercase first letters) - actually no, in C# records, positional parameters generate properties with the SAME casing as the parameter names. So `public record Person(string name, int age)` generates properties `name` and `age` (lowercase).\n\n\nBy default, `System.Text.Json` serializes using the property names as-is, so you'd get `{\"name\":\"...\",\"age\":...}`. To get PascalCase output like `{\"Name\":\"...\",\"Age\":...}`, I need to apply a naming policy that converts to PascalCase. Let me verify when `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` was actually introduced in the .NET framework.\n\nLooking at the timeline, .NET 8 added several snake_case and kebab-case variants, but I'm not certain if PascalCase was included in .NET 9 or if it's coming in a later version. Since the user is asking about .NET 11, which is beyond my knowledge cutoff, it's possible this feature was added or will be added by then.\n\nLet me just try creating a project targeting .NET 11 and see what's available on the system. If the SDK isn't installed, I'll work with what I have, and if `JsonNamingPolicy.PascalCase` doesn't exist, I'll find an alternative approach.","outputTokens":1057,"requestId":"CC19:281CF9:1347759:15ADE92:69F93E1A"},"id":"3edf942c-2ba9-413a-9e63-abf068d7f56b","timestamp":"2026-05-05T00:47:41.335Z","parentId":"fd0b378e-c742-4fef-b202-e5c22923e172"}
